{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3f9d21da-4949-441b-8645-7ff35c51ac03","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to **abstract file I/O behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n1. **Define an interface:**\n   ```csharp\n   public interface IFileSystem\n   {\n       string ReadAllText(string path);\n       void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n       bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n   }\n   ```\n\n2. **Create a real implementation** that delegates to `System.IO`:\n   ```csharp\n   public class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n   {\n       public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n       public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n       public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n   }\n   ```\n\n3. **Inject `IFileSystem`** into classes that need it, then **mock it in tests**.\n\n**Alternatively**, if you're on .NET 8+, `System.IO.Abstractions` is a popular NuGet package that provides exactly this — a ready-made `IFileSystem` interface plus an in-memory test file system (`MockFileSystem`). It saves you from maintaining the wrapper yourself.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b70e421-6a8c-4117-8728-440b3f0cfc0b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to make file system operations (`File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, `Directory.Exists`) testable in their .NET project. This is a design/architecture question, not a code change request.\n\nThe standard approach is to abstract file system operations behind an interface, then use dependency injection so you can swap in a mock/fake implementation during testing.\n\nLet me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":397,"requestId":"768B:18DC0C:CAE7AC:EC0CAC:69F2B60E"},"id":"c6a372aa-f5ba-4504-8287-2f1c900c5094","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:53:26.686Z","parentId":"cb4815a0-abf3-4c10-8398-df42cfc845b2"}
